# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bill-terry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bill-terry/1922-new-york-giants-season] The **1922 New York Giants season** was the franchise's 40th season.
[src:bill-terry/1922-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in first place in the National League with a 93–61 record.
[src:bill-terry/1922-new-york-giants-season] The Giants won their second consecutive World Series, defeating the New York Yankees in five games (Game 2 was a 3–3 tie) without a loss.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The **1923 major league baseball season** began on April 17, 1923.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 7, with the New York Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 20th World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 6 on October 15.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] In the third consecutive iteration of the Subway Series, the Yankees defeated the Giants, four games to two, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third World Series between the two teams, and the first to see the Yankees win over the Giants.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1922 season.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second of eight seasons that "League Awards", a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), were issued.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Only an American League award was given in 1923.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The 1923 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 17 with all teams playing, while American League Opening Day took place the following day with all teams playing.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 7.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 15.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (5 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 15 with the New York Yankees defeating the New York Giants in the 1923 World Series in six games.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Yankees leave the Polo Grounds, where they shared with the New York Giants for the previous 10 seasons, and open Yankee Stadium, where they would play for 84 seasons through 1973 and 1976 through 2008.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees, whose home had been Manhattan for their entire existence, moved into the Bronx where they remain to this day.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] Referring to the Philadelphia Phillies' home at National League Park, on July 11, *The Philadelphia Inquirer* coined the term Baker Bowl.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] "Baker Bowl" became a common name for the stadium until its closure in 1938, although the Phillies would still refer to the venue as its official "National League Park" name in newspaper advertisements.
[src:bill-terry/1923-major-league-baseball-season] On August 21, Clark Griffith, owner of the Washington Senators since 1920, announced that National Park would be named after himself, Griffith Stadium.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] The **1924 Washington Senators** won 92 games, lost 62, and finished in first place in the American League.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] Fueled by the excitement of winning their first AL pennant, the Senators won the World Series in dramatic fashion, a 12-inning Game 7 victory.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] The Senators' offense was led by future Hall of Famer Goose Goslin, who was one of the youngest players on the team.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] Walter Johnson had another outstanding year, winning the American League pitching Triple Crown and being voted Most Valuable Player.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] He anchored a staff that allowed the fewest runs in the league.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] Reliever Firpo Marberry paced the circuit in saves and games pitched.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] Manager Bucky Harris, who was also the team's starting second baseman, was the highest paid player on the team, earning $9,000.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] The Senators drew 584,310 fans to their 77 home games at Griffith Stadium, good for 4th place among the 8 American League teams and an average of 7,588 per game.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] Note: Firpo Marberry was team leader and MLB leader in saves with 15.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] The Senators finally made it into the postseason after many years of being the laughingstock of the American League.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] Behind ace pitcher Walter Johnson, they won the deciding Game Seven 4-3 in extra innings.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] The team returned to the World Series the next year and also in 1933, losing both, their last Series while playing in Washington.
[src:bill-terry/1924-washington-senators-season] It wasn’t until 2019 that an MLB team based in the District of Columbia won another World Series.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The **1924 World Series** was the championship series of the 1924 Major League Baseball season.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The 21st edition of the World Series was a best-of-seven playoff matching the American League (AL) champion Washington Senators against the National League (NL) champion New York Giants, with the Senators defeating the Giants in seven games to win their first championship in club history.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] This was the first major professional sports championship ever won by a Washington, D.C.-based team.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The Giants became the first team to play in four consecutive World Series, winning in 1921–1922 and losing in 1923–1924, and their veteran manager, John McGraw, made his ninth and final World Series appearance.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The deciding game of the Series was decided in extra innings, the second such occurrence in MLB history (the first had occurred in 1912).
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Walter Johnson, nearing the end of his playing career at age 36, made his first ever World Series appearance, having completed his first 20-win season since 1919 (with 23 wins).
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] He lost both of his two starts, but was awarded a win in Game 7 with a relief appearance in which he held the Giants scoreless over the final four innings, helping the Senators secure their first championship.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Game 7 is widely considered one of the most dramatic in World Series history.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Johnson struck out 12 Giants batters in Game 1 in a losing cause.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Although that total matched Ed Walsh's number in the 1906 World Series, it came in 12 innings.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Johnson struck out only nine in the first nine innings.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] In Game 7, with the Senators behind 3–1 in the eighth, Bucky Harris hit a routine ground ball to third which hit a pebble and took a bad hop over Giants third baseman Freddie Lindstrom.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Two runners scored on the play, tying the score at three.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Walter Johnson then came in to pitch the ninth, and held the Giants scoreless into extra innings.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] With the score still 3–3, Washington came up in the 12th.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] With one out, and runners on first and second, Earl McNeely hit another grounder at Lindstrom, and again the ball took a bad hop, scoring Muddy Ruel with the Series-winning run.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] This was the first World Series to use the 2–3–2 home game pattern, which would be adapted as the permanent format beginning the following year.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] This was the Senators' only World Series championship victory during the franchise's time in Washington.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] In 1961, the Senators relocated to Minnesota and were rebranded as the Twins, and subsequently won the World Series in 1987 and in 1991.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] This would be the last World Series win for a Washington based team until the Washington Nationals, who were originally the Montreal Expos, won the World Series in 2019, 95 years after the Senators' only triumph.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] In 2020, ESPN named it the third greatest World Series of all-time.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The Senators tied it at 2–2 with a run in the bottom of the ninth.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The Giants scored two in the top of the 12th off the Big Train; Washington fought back for a run in the bottom of the inning, but left the tying run on third.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Washington fought back early in the game, scoring 3 runs in 5 innings.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] But the Giants would quickly fight back in the final three frames to tie the game as it went to the bottom of the ninth.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] With Joe Judge representing the potential winning run and 1 out, Roger Peckinpaugh hit a double to win the game and tie the series.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Ossie Bluege, the only man reliever Claude Jonnard faced, drew a bases-loaded walk to make it 6-4.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Mule Watson then came in to nail down the last two outs.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Rosy Ryan's fourth-inning home run is to date the only World Series home run by a relief pitcher and the only postseason home run by a relief pitcher until Travis Wood in 2016.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Goose Goslin had a big game for the Senators, with three singles and a home run to go 4-for-4 and drive in four runs.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Johnson again pitched a complete game but the Giants recorded 13 hits off him, taking a 3–2 lead in the Series.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Bentley broke a 1–1 tie in the fifth with a two-run home run, the second homer by a New York pitcher in the Series after Rosy Ryan's in Game 3.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Both Washington runs scored on a single in the fifth inning by manager Bucky Harris.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Tom Zachary won his second game of the series, deadlocking the series at three games each.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The unheralded Curly Ogden was given the Game 7 start for Washington – it was his only World Series appearance.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] He struck out a batter and walked one, and then was pulled for George Mogridge.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] It was later revealed that manager Bucky Harris started righthander Ogden so that the Giants would be locked into their "righthanded" lineup, before he switched to the lefthander Mogridge.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] With the Senators trailing 3–1 in the eighth inning with bases loaded and two outs, Bucky Harris hit a "bad hop" ground ball to third, that reportedly struck a pebble, which Freddie Lindstrom failed to catch (no error was charged).
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] As a result, two runs scored for a 3–3 tie.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] In the ninth inning, Walter Johnson would step up as pitcher and pitch four scoreless innings.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] In the bottom of the 12th inning, Giants catcher Hank Gowdy stepped on his own discarded mask while trying to catch a Muddy Ruel foul pop-up, and dropped the ball for an error.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Given a second chance in the at-bat, Ruel doubled.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Johnson reached first on another error, and with Ruel on second and Johnson on first, Earl McNeely hit a "bad hop" ground ball to Lindstrom that was almost identical to Harris' eighth inning hit.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] Lindstrom again failed to catch the ball (reportedly hitting the same pebble that was struck four innings earlier) as it bounced over him into left field, and Ruel scored the series-winning run.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The game holds the record as the longest Game 7 (by innings) in MLB postseason history.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] It was also the first World Series Game 7 to be decided in extra innings (although the 1912 series ended with a ten-inning Game 8), and the last until 1991.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] In 2014, on the Series' 90th anniversary, the Library of Congress acquired a newsreel of highlight footage from Game 7, including McNeely's Series-winning base hit.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] CNN subsequently released this footage on its website.
[src:bill-terry/1924-world-series] The next time a Washington team won the World Series would come 95 years later in 2019, when the Washington Nationals did so against the Houston Astros.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The **1932 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1932.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 25, with the Chicago Cubs and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 29th World Series on September 28 and ended with Game 4 on October 2.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The Yankees swept the Cubs in four games, capturing their fourth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1928.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the St.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, the Brooklyn Robins reverted to their 1913 name, the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The 1932 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 11 with the Boston Red Sox and Washington Senators playing, while National League Opening Day took place the following day.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 25 and featured all sixteen teams, continuing the trend which began with the 1930 season.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 28 and October 2.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (3 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 28 and ended on October 2 with the New York Yankees sweeping the Chicago Cubs in the 1932 World Series in four games.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] Across 77 homes games, the Boston Red Sox played their Tuesday, April 19 doubleheader against the New York Yankees and their first four of their 16 Sunday games at the Boston Braves home field of Braves Field (the remaining 71 home games were played at Fenway Park).
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four consecutive season playing some (mostly Sunday) games at Braves Field.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] The stadium was previously home of the single-season National Football League team that was also named the Cleveland Indians.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the 1st of 12 seasons since that saw the Indians play at both venues, occurring again in every season from 1936 to 1946.
[src:bill-terry/1932-major-league-baseball-season] To this point, the Indians played all 32 of their seasons since their inaugural 1901 season at League Park.
[src:bill-terry/1932-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The **1932 New York Giants season** was the 50th for the franchise.
[src:bill-terry/1932-new-york-giants-mlb-season] The team finished in a tie for sixth place in the National League with a 72–82 record, 18 games behind the Chicago Cubs.
[src:bill-terry/1932-new-york-giants-mlb-season] Although the Giants did not contend for the National League pennant, 1932 was still a significant season in the future of the franchise.
[src:bill-terry/1932-new-york-giants-mlb-season] Firstly, midway through the season, longtime manager John McGraw stepped down, and he named hard-hitting star first baseman Bill Terry as his successor.
[src:bill-terry/1932-new-york-giants-mlb-season] Secondly, converted outfielder and future Hall of Famer Freddie Lindstrom was in his final season with the Giants before a trade to the Pirates prior to the 1933 season.
[src:bill-terry/1932-new-york-giants-mlb-season] Finally, this was the first season in which the Giants featured numbers on the uniforms.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1933 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the first edition of the All-Star Game known as the "Midsummer Classic".
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first official playing of the midseason exhibition baseball game between Major League Baseball's (MLB's) National League (NL) and American League (AL) All-Star teams.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 6, 1933, at Comiskey Park in Chicago, Illinois, the home of the AL's Chicago White Sox.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the AL defeating the NL, 4–2, in two hours and five minutes.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The first official All-Star Game came 22 years after the Addie Joss Benefit Game of July 24, 1911, when the American League's Cleveland Naps faced a team of all-stars from other American League teams at League Park in Cleveland, Ohio; the game was won by the all-star squad, 5–3.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The first official MLB All-Star exhibition game on July 6, 1933, was held at Comiskey Park (1910–1990) and was part of the 1933 Chicago World's Fair during the city's centennial.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 1933 MLB All-Star Game was the idea of Arch Ward, the sports editor of the *Chicago Tribune*, after the Mayor of Chicago, Edward J.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Kelly, had first approached the *Tribune's* publisher for a major sport event.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was intended to be a one-time event to boost morale during the Great Depression.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ward decided that the fans would select the starting nine players and the managers the other nine players for each of the NL and AL All-Star teams.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The *Tribune* called it the "Game of the Century", and 55 newspapers across the country printed the fans' ballots in their papers.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The *Tribune* estimated the game's attendance on July 6, 1933, at 49,000.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The proceeds ($45,000, net gate receipts) from the game went to a charity for disabled and needy major league players.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The All-Star Game would afterwards be known as MLB's "Midsummer Classic".
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The legendary Babe Ruth of the Yankees highlighted the game by hitting a two-run home run to right field in the bottom of the third inning and catching a fly ball up against the scoreboard in right-center field in the top of the eighth inning.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ruth was greeted at home plate by the AL/Chicago White Sox batboy John McBride and teammate Lou Gehrig.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Twenty of the game's thirty-six All-Stars including Ruth would later be inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame at Cooperstown, New York.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Both the game's managers, five out of six coaches, and two out of the four umpires on the field that day would also be future Hall of Famers.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Two AL All-Stars were White Sox players, starting third baseman Jimmy Dykes and starting center fielder Al Simmons.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Yankee Lefty Gomez was the winning pitcher for the American League.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL team wore specially made gray uniforms and navy blue caps with "National League" in navy blue felt letters on the front of the jersey, a large navy blue felt number on the back and "NL" in white letters printed on the navy caps.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL team members each wore their home uniform.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL members were allowed to keep their All-Star uniforms and caps.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In 1934, each NL member used their home uniform and cap.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game's official AL baseball was changed to an official NL baseball and the AL home plate umpire was replaced by a NL home plate umpire after the top of the 5th inning.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] 60 baseballs autographed by All-Star players were given out before the game started.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Personnel in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Klem moving behind the plate.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Chick Hafey of the National League had the first hit, a bloop single to center field to lead off the second inning.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League got on the board first in the bottom of the second.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] NL pitcher Bill Hallahan issued one-out walks to Jimmy Dykes and Joe Cronin.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Two batters later, the game's winning pitcher Lefty Gomez, singled home Dykes for the AL's first run.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the bottom of the third, after a walk to Charlie Gehringer, Babe Ruth famously hit the first home run in All-Star Game history, putting the AL up 3–0.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Hallahan was chased from the game after walking Lou Gehrig immediately afterward, and was replaced by Lon Warneke.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] General Crowder replaced Gomez to start the fourth inning.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the sixth, Warneke hit a one-out triple and scored on a Pepper Martin groundout.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Frankie Frisch followed with a home run to bring the NL to within a run, but after a Chuck Klein single, Crowder would escape the inning without giving up any more damage.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Cronin led off the bottom of the sixth with a single.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After advancing on a bunt, he scored on an Earl Averill single to extend the lead to 4–2.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Crowder would be replaced by Lefty Grove in the top of the seventh, while Warneke was replaced by Carl Hubbell in the bottom of the inning.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL looked to have a chance in the top of the eighth.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With Frisch on first with two outs, Hafey lined a shot to right field that looked like it could be a home run, but Ruth reached over the wall to catch it, denying the NL a chance to tie the game.
[src:bill-terry/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Grove retired the side in order in the ninth to secure the American League's victory.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Born in Atlanta, Terry made his professional baseball debut in 1915 at the age of 16.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He began his career as a pitcher, playing for two separate minor league teams, the Newnan Cowetas of the Georgia–Alabama League and the Dothan, Alabama based Dothan club of the FLAG League.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] With Newnan, he had a win–loss record of 7–1, with an 0.60 earned run average in eight games.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] After starting 1916 with Newnan, by the end of the year he had moved up to the class-B Shreveport Gassers of the Texas League.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He again compiled impressive statistics for his new team, putting up a record of 6–2 with a 1.07 earned run average in 11 games with Shreveport.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry spent all of 1917 with Shreveport, with a record of 14–11 and an earned run average of 3.00.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] By this time, he was also beginning to play more in the field, pitching in 40 games and appearing in 55 other games.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] After spending several years playing semi-professionally, Terry was picked up by the Toledo Mud Hens of the American Association in 1922.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He was now playing in double-A, the highest minor league level at that time.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] While he was still pitching, putting up a 9–9 record in 26 games, his hitting was also starting to pick up.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 88 games with Toledo, Terry batted .336 with 14 home runs.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1923, Terry had been converted into a full-time first baseman.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 109 games with Toledo that year, Terry batted .377 with 15 home runs.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] This gained the notice of the major league New York Giants, and on September 18 they purchased his contract from the Mud Hens.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In an interesting coincidence, Freddie Lindstrom, another future Hall of Fame player, was also purchased by the Giants from the Mud Hens on the same day.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry made his major league debut with the Giants on September 24, 1923 in a game against the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In that game, he pinch-hit for Giants pitcher Rosy Ryan, going 0-for-1.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry did not play again until September 30, when he made his first appearance in the starting lineup against the Boston Braves.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry got his first major league hit in that game, going 1-for-3 and scoring his first major league run.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry finished the season with one hit in seven at bats in three games.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry played all of 1924 with the Giants, backing up fellow future Hall of Famer George Kelly at first base for the pennant-winning team.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry played in 77 games, 35 at first base and the rest as a pinch-hitter.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He batted .239 with 5 home runs and 24 runs batted in.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In the World Series against the Washington Senators, he batted .429, including a Game 1 home run off Walter Johnson.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1925, Giants starting third baseman Heinie Groh suffered an injury early in the season, forcing the team to juggle its lineup a bit.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Starting second baseman Frankie Frisch was tried at third but wound up spending most of the season shifting around the infield when Lindstrom was made the starter.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Kelly was moved from first base to second, and Terry was installed as the starting first baseman.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He hit .319 in 133 games, with 11 homers and 70 runs batted in.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1926, with Lindstrom established as the starter at third, Frisch was reinstated at second and Kelly moved back to first, sending Terry back into a reserve role.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In addition to backing up Kelly, Terry played in 14 games in the outfield.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] This was the only season in which he played more than one game at a position other than first base.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Overall, Terry played 98 games, batting .289 with 5 home runs and 43 runs batted in.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] During the following offseason, the Giants made some major changes to their starting lineup.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] On December 20, 1926, they traded Frisch and pitcher Jimmy Ring to the St.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Then, on February 9, they traded Kelly to the Reds for outfielder Edd Roush, opening a spot once more for Terry in the starting lineup.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry batted .326 in 1927, with 20 home runs and 121 runs batted in.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He finished 13th in the voting for the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award, and his days of being a backup were behind him for good.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Over the next two seasons, Terry continued to produce for the Giants, batting .326 again in 1928 with 101 runs batted in, and then .372 in 1929 with 117 runs batted in.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In both years, he finished in the top ten in the National League in a number of statistical categories and in 1929 he finished third in the Most Valuable Player Award voting.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] This led to what is generally considered Terry's best season ever, 1930.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He finished first in the National League with a .401 batting average, the first player to hit over .400 since Rogers Hornsby in 1925.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] It is also the last time to date that anyone in the National League has hit .400.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Only Ted Williams of the American League's Boston Red Sox in 1941 has hit .400 since.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry also led the league with 254 hits, which is tied for the most in NL history with the Phillies' Lefty O'Doul's 254 in 1929.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He also finished 5th in the league in on-base percentage (.452), 7th in slugging percentage (.619), 6th in runs scored with 139 runs, and led the league in putouts and assists by a first baseman.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] While there was no official league most valuable player award in 1930, Terry won *The Sporting News* Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] While Terry never again reached the lofty heights of 1930, he had another excellent season in 1931.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He led the league in runs scored with 121 and in triples with 20 while batting .349 with 112 runs batted in, and he finished third in the new Baseball Writers' Association of America National League Most Valuable Player Award voting.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He became the only Giants player (as of 2014) to hit two doubles and two triples in a game when he did so against the Cincinnati Reds on September 13, 1931.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1932, Terry set his career high in home runs with 28, batting .350 with 117 runs batted in.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He was also named the team's manager in early June, replacing the legendary John McGraw.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He hit three home runs in a game in a losing effort against the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] The team finished in sixth place, going 55–59 under Terry.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1933, Terry's first full season as manager, the team won the National League pennant and the World Series.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Although, as a player, Terry missed a month early in the season with an injury, he still hit .322.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] It was also the first season of the All-Star Game, for which Terry was chosen as a starter and in which he got two hits.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] The Giants once again faced the Senators in the 1933 World Series, which they won four games to one.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry went 6-for-22, hitting a home run in Game 4 off Monte Weaver.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Despite an off-year, Terry still finished fourth in the MVP voting, perhaps gaining votes for managing the team to the championship, the Giants' first since 1922, the year before Terry's MLB debut.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1934 Terry came back to put up big numbers once more, finishing second in the NL in batting at .354 and in hits with 213 while finishing seventh in the Most Valuable Player Award voting.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry managed the team to a seven-game lead in the National League on September 6, but the Giants lost 13 of their final 21 games and fell to second place at season's end, just two games behind the pennant-winning St.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1935, Terry again got over 200 hits with 203, and batted .341 while finishing sixth in the Most Valuable Player Award voting, and managed the team to a third-place finish.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In both years he was again selected to start in the All-Star game.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] As manager, Terry became an advocate of platooning, as Hank Leiber and Jimmy Ripple split playing time in center field.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Before the season started, the team had purchased Sam Leslie from the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry split time at first base with Leslie, with the newcomer getting the lion's share.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] It worked out well for the team, as they again won the pennant, beating the Cardinals by five games.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In the World Series, Terry started all six games, but batted just .240 with no extra base hits.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He had five runs batted in, but that was not enough, as the Giants lost to the New York Yankees, four games to two.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry retired as a player after the 1936 season, but continued to manage the Giants until 1941.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He also held the title of general manager of the Giants from September 7, 1937, through the end of the 1942 season.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] The Giants won another pennant in 1937, but they lost another World Series to the New York Yankees, four games to one.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] The team finished third in 1938, but never again finished in the first division under Terry, finishing fifth, sixth, and fifth in his last three years as manager.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry resigned as manager after the 1941 season and named Mel Ott, his teammate since 1926, as his successor.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] After retiring from playing and managing, Terry settled in Jacksonville, Florida, where he owned a successful Buick automobile dealership and purchased the Jacksonville Braves double-A team in 1958.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry retired with 1120 runs scored, 154 home runs, 1078 runs batted in and a .341 batting average.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] He also currently holds the record for the highest career batting average for a left-handed hitter in the National League at .341.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry was also one of the best fielding first baseman of his era, compiling a career .992 fielding percentage.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry accumulated 7 five-hit games and 40 four-hit games in his MLB career.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] As a manager, he led the Giants to three National League pennants and a world championship.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In nine full seasons as a manager, he only had a losing season twice while finishing in the top three of the League six times.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] No Giants manager would lead them to three league pennants until Bruce Bochy did so nearly seventy years later.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] Terry was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1954.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] In 1999, he ranked number 59 on *The Sporting News'* list of the 100 Greatest Baseball Players, and was a nominee for the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:bill-terry/bill-terry] 3 in 1984; it is posted on the facade of the upper deck in the left field corner of Oracle Park.
